--- body ---
## Context

All sliding-window null models (S1–S4, L1–L2, C2ST, G1–G9) use Monte
Carlo permutation: draw n_perm=500 random full shuffles of the before+after
pool, recompute the test statistic each time, report mean and std of the
null distribution.

Two problems:
1. SE(null_mean) ≈ σ_null / √500 ≈ 4.5% error on the ribbon position.
   For large-n windows this dominates the signal.
2. p-value resolution is 1/n_perm = 0.002; values reported as "p=0.000"
   are actually "p < 0.002".

The fix: derive E[T | H₀] and Var[T | H₀] analytically for each
two-sample statistic.  These are exact (up to asymptotic approximation)
and require zero Monte Carlo draws.  For large-n windows (CLT regime),
the analytical values are strictly better than 500 permutations.

## Permutation structure

Each (year, window) test pools n_before + n_after documents and shuffles
ALL of them (full Fisher-Yates permutation), reassigning the first n_before
to "before" and the rest to "after".  Only documents within the window
participate — the full corpus is never touched outside the window.

## Analytical nulls by method

### S2 — energy distance
E(D_energy | H₀) = 2 * E[||X−Y||] − E[||X−X'||] − E[||Y−Y'||]
where X, Y drawn iid from the pooled empirical distribution.
These expectations are means of entries in the pairwise distance matrix,
computable in O(N²) from the pooled embeddings.
Var can be derived from 4th-moment U-statistics (see Székely & Rizzo 2013).

### S1 — MMD²
E(MMD² | H₀) = 0 (biased estimator) or
E(MMD²_unbiased | H₀) = 0 by construction.
Var(MMD²_unbiased | H₀) from Gretton et al. (2012) Lemma 6:
  Var ≈ (4/n²) × (Var of h(X,X') under H₀)
where h is the kernel function.  Exact in O(N²).

### L1 — JS divergence
Under H₀ (shared vocabulary distribution), JS divergence between two
multinomial samples of sizes n_before, n_after from shared distribution p
satisfies:
  E[JS] ≈ (V−1)/(4) × (1/n_before + 1/n_after)   (leading term)
  Var[JS] = O(1/n²)
where V = vocabulary size.  This is the first-order analytic correction
(Archer et al. 2014).  Requires only the pooled TF-IDF mean and vocabulary
size — O(V) to compute.

### G methods (G1, G5, G6, G8) — citation scalar metrics
These compute |Δ metric(before) − Δ metric(after)| where the metric is
a summary of a citation graph.  Under node-label permutation, the analytic
null requires the variance of the metric under uniform random node splits.
This is harder; leave for a follow-up unless easy closed forms exist.

### C2ST — AUC
Under H₀ (no separability), AUC → 0.5 with variance O(1/(n_before*n_after))
from the Mann-Whitney U-statistic identity.  Exact analytic null available
via Hanley & McNeil (1982).

## Relevant files

- `scripts/compute_null_model.py` — dispatcher; add `--analytical` flag
- `scripts/_permutation_accel.py` — GPU/CPU permutation backends; add
  analytical implementations alongside Monte Carlo
- `scripts/_permutation_lexical.py` — L1/L2 backends
- `scripts/_permutation_citation.py` — G method backends
- `config/analysis.yaml` — add `analytical: true` toggle per method

## Actions

1. Add `compute_analytical_null(method, X_before, X_after, cfg) →
   (null_mean, null_std)` in `_permutation_accel.py` for S1 (MMD) and
   S2 (energy distance).

2. Add analytical null for L1 (JS divergence) in `_permutation_lexical.py`.

3. Add analytical null for C2ST (AUC via Mann-Whitney) in a new
   `_permutation_c2st.py` or in `_divergence_c2st.py`.

4. Add `--analytical` flag to `compute_null_model.py`; when set, skip
   Monte Carlo loops and call the analytical functions instead.

5. Update `divergence.mk` null model recipes to pass `--analytical` for
   S1, S2, L1, C2ST methods.

6. Leave G methods on Monte Carlo for now; add a `# TODO: analytical`
   comment.

## Test

Red: for each analytical method, assert that the analytical null_mean and
null_std are within 2× SE of the Monte Carlo estimates computed with
n_perm=5000 on a fixture with n_before=n_after=200.

## Verification

- [ ] Analytical null_mean matches Monte Carlo (n_perm=5000) within 2 SE
  for S1, S2, L1, C2ST on the fixture
- [ ] Null CSV files are regenerated; ribbon shape is smoother
  (no Monte Carlo noise across years)
- [ ] `make check-fast` passes

## Invariants

- Monte Carlo path must remain as fallback (keep n_perm flag, add
  `--analytical` as opt-in)
- Output CSV schema (null_mean, null_std, z_score, p_value) unchanged

## Exit criteria

- Analytical null implemented for S1, S2, L1, C2ST
- Tests pass
- PR merged
